\details{
\code{Prior_Setup()} initializes a structured set of prior parameters for generalized linear models (GLMs), supporting both Gaussian and non-Gaussian families.
It is designed to provide the full set of inputs required for multiple prior specifications (referred to as "pfamilies"), including conjugate normal priors,
Normal-Gamma priors, and independent normal-gamma priors.

The function returns a list containing:
\itemize{
\item \code{mu}: the prior mean vector
\item \code{Sigma}: the prior variance-covariance matrix
\item \code{Sigma_0}: for \code{family = gaussian()}, the dispersion-independent coefficient
prior covariance matrix on the precision-weighted scale (the \eqn{\Sigma_0} passed
into \code{\link{compute_gaussian_prior}}): the Zellner \code{Sigma} before calibration,
divided by the classical weighted residual variance
\eqn{\sum_i w_i r_i^2/(n_{\mathrm{effective}}-2)} from the internal \code{glm.fit}.
\code{NULL} for non-Gaussian families.
\item \code{dispersion}: the estimated dispersion (for Gaussian models)
\item \code{shape}: the shape parameter for Normal-Gamma priors (if applicable)
\item \code{rate}: the rate parameter for Normal-Gamma priors (if applicable)
\item \code{coefficients}: named numeric vector, same length and names as columns of \code{x}; a point
estimate for the regression coefficients (currently \code{coef()} of the internal full-model
GLM fit, i.e. the MLE under that model). Intended mainly as \code{beta} in \code{\link{dGamma}()}
and related \code{prior_list} entries when updating dispersion with fixed coefficients.
This is distinct from \code{mu}, which holds prior means.
\item \code{model}: the model frame used to construct the design matrix
\item \code{x}: the model matrix used
\item \code{y}: the response used
\item \code{call}: the matched call to \code{Prior_Setup()}
\item \code{PriorSettings}: a list of metadata including:
\itemize{
\item \code{pwt}: prior weight (scalar or vector)
\item \code{n_prior}: effective prior sample size
\item \code{n_likelihood}: effective likelihood sample size
\item \code{intercept_source}: method used to set the prior mean for the intercept
\item \code{effects_source}: method used to set the prior mean for the effects
}
}
\subsection{Connection to \code{pfamily} constructors and \code{prior_list}}{

Call \code{Prior_Setup(formula, family = \dots)} (with \code{data},
\code{weights}, etc. as needed) so \code{mu}, \code{Sigma}, and (for
Gaussian families) \code{dispersion}, \code{shape}, and \code{rate} are
on the scale implied by the likelihood and your \code{pwt} / \code{n_prior}.
The recommended mapping from the returned list into a \code{\link{pfamily}}
or into \code{prior_list} for \code{\link{simfuncs}} follows the worked
patterns in \code{example("Prior_Setup")} (\code{inst/examples/Ex_Prior_Setup.R}).
Distinct priors use \strong{different} combinations of coefficient-scale \code{Sigma},
dispersion-free \code{Sigma_0} (Gaussian, for \code{\link{dNormal_Gamma}} /
\code{\link{rNormalGamma_reg}}), and \code{dNormal(..., dispersion = ...)}; mixing
these up is a common error.
\subsection{\code{\link{dNormal}()}}{
\itemize{
\item \strong{Typical use (e.g. Poisson \code{\link{glmb}}):} \code{dNormal(mu = ps$mu, Sigma = ps$Sigma)}.
\item \strong{Gaussian with fixed dispersion (\code{\link{lmb}} / \code{\link{rlmb}}):}
pass \code{dispersion = ps2$dispersion} as well:
\code{dNormal(mu = ps2$mu, Sigma = ps2$Sigma, dispersion = ps2$dispersion)}.
